      ## Problem definition:
      ​
      Fraud detection is the process of identifying and preventing fraudulent activities and transactions. It involves the use of various techniques and tools, such as machine learning algorithms, data analysis, and behavioral analysis, to identify and prevent illegal activities that aim to defraud individuals or organizations. Fraud detection is crucial in various industries, such as banking, insurance, and e-commerce, as it helps to protect businesses and customers from financial losses and other negative consequences associated with fraud. The ultimate goal of fraud detection is to provide a secure and trustworthy environment for transactions, ensuring the integrity and stability of the financial system.
      ​
      ## Case Study:
      Blossom Bank(BB PLC)
      ​
      Blossom Bank also known as BB PLC is a multinational financial services group, that offers retail and investment banking, pension management, asset management and payments services, headquartered in London, UK and will like to put in place a preventive measure which will predict online payment fraud using machine learning models.
      ​
      ## Project AIM :
      This project aims to achive that using the data set of previous transactions from Blossom Bank.
      ​
      ## Expected Outcome:
      An accurate and efficient fraud detection system that can detect fraudulent transactions in real-time. Improved ability to identify and prevent online payment fraud, reducing financial losses for the bank and increasing customer trust. Increased operational efficiency and cost savings by reducing the manual workload involved in detecting fraud.
      ​
      An accurate and efficient fraud detection system that can detect fraudulent transactions in real-time. Improved ability to identify and prevent online payment fraud, reducing financial losses for the bank and increasing customer trust. Increased operational efficiency and cost savings by reducing the manual workload involved in detecting fraud.
      ​
      The Blossom Bank will benefit from the fraud detection solution in several ways:
      ​
      1.Reduction in financial losses: By accurately detecting and preventing fraudulent transactions, the bank will be able to reduce its financial losses, ensuring that its customers' funds are protected.
      ​
      2.Improved operational efficiency: Automated fraud detection systems can significantly reduce the manual workload involved in detecting fraud, leading to improved operational efficiency and cost savings for the bank.
      ​
      3.Increased customer trust: By implementing a robust fraud detection system, the bank can demonstrate its commitment to security and improve customer trust in its ability to protect their funds.
      ​
      4.Early detection of fraud: With real-time fraud detection, the bank will be able to identify fraudulent transactions early on, reducing the potential impact of the fraud.
      ​
      5.Improved regulatory compliance: Fraud detection systems can help the bank meet regulatory requirements, ensuring that it is operating within the law and protecting the interests of its customers and stakeholders.
      ​
      Overall, the implementation of a fraud detection solution will provide Blossom Bank with a more secure and trustworthy environment for transactions, reducing its financial losses and improving its operational efficiency and customer trust.
      ​
      ## OBJECTIVES OF PROJECT:
      To develop a fraud detection system that can accurately detect fraudulent transactions in real-time.
      ​
      To reduce the number of false positive cases, meaning legitimate transactions being wrongly identified as fraud.
      ​
      To improve the efficiency of the bank's existing fraud detection system by reducing the time it takes to identify fraudulent transactions.
      ​
      To provide the bank with actionable insights and recommendations on how to prevent future fraud.
      ​
      ## METHODOLOGY:
      Data collection: The first step will involve collecting relevant data from the bank's database, including transaction history, customer demographics, and other relevant information.
      ​
      Data pre-processing: The collected data will then undergo cleaning, normalization, and transformation to ensure its quality and suitability for analysis.
      ​
      Exploratory data analysis: This step involves examining the data to understand the relationships and patterns between the different variables. This will also help to identify any missing values, outliers, or other anomalies that may impact the model's accuracy.
      ​
      Feature selection: This step involves selecting the most important variables that will be used to build the predictive model. The aim is to identify variables that have a significant impact on the outcome of the model.
      ​
      Model selection: A range of machine learning algorithms will be considered for the task of fraud detection. The model with the highest accuracy rate will be selected and fine-tuned to improve its performance.
      ​
      Model evaluation: The selected model will be evaluated using a range of performance metrics, including accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score.
      ​
      Deployment: The final step is to deploy the model in the bank's systems to start detecting fraudulent transactions in real-time.

      Problem definition:¶

      Fraud detection is the process of identifying and preventing fraudulent activities and transactions. It involves the use of various techniques and tools, such as machine learning algorithms, data analysis, and behavioral analysis, to identify and prevent illegal activities that aim to defraud individuals or organizations. Fraud detection is crucial in various industries, such as banking, insurance, and e-commerce, as it helps to protect businesses and customers from financial losses and other negative consequences associated with fraud. The ultimate goal of fraud detection is to provide a secure and trustworthy environment for transactions, ensuring the integrity and stability of the financial system.

      Case Study:¶

      Blossom Bank(BB PLC)

      Blossom Bank also known as BB PLC is a multinational financial services group, that offers retail and investment banking, pension management, asset management and payments services, headquartered in London, UK and will like to put in place a preventive measure which will predict online payment fraud using machine learning models.

      Project AIM :¶

      This project aims to achive that using the data set of previous transactions from Blossom Bank.

      Expected Outcome:¶

      An accurate and efficient fraud detection system that can detect fraudulent transactions in real-time. Improved ability to identify and prevent online payment fraud, reducing financial losses for the bank and increasing customer trust. Increased operational efficiency and cost savings by reducing the manual workload involved in detecting fraud.

      An accurate and efficient fraud detection system that can detect fraudulent transactions in real-time. Improved ability to identify and prevent online payment fraud, reducing financial losses for the bank and increasing customer trust. Increased operational efficiency and cost savings by reducing the manual workload involved in detecting fraud.

      The Blossom Bank will benefit from the fraud detection solution in several ways:

      1.Reduction in financial losses: By accurately detecting and preventing fraudulent transactions, the bank will be able to reduce its financial losses, ensuring that its customers' funds are protected.

      2.Improved operational efficiency: Automated fraud detection systems can significantly reduce the manual workload involved in detecting fraud, leading to improved operational efficiency and cost savings for the bank.

      3.Increased customer trust: By implementing a robust fraud detection system, the bank can demonstrate its commitment to security and improve customer trust in its ability to protect their funds.

      4.Early detection of fraud: With real-time fraud detection, the bank will be able to identify fraudulent transactions early on, reducing the potential impact of the fraud.

      5.Improved regulatory compliance: Fraud detection systems can help the bank meet regulatory requirements, ensuring that it is operating within the law and protecting the interests of its customers and stakeholders.

      Overall, the implementation of a fraud detection solution will provide Blossom Bank with a more secure and trustworthy environment for transactions, reducing its financial losses and improving its operational efficiency and customer trust.

      OBJECTIVES OF PROJECT:¶

      To develop a fraud detection system that can accurately detect fraudulent transactions in real-time.

      To reduce the number of false positive cases, meaning legitimate transactions being wrongly identified as fraud.

      To improve the efficiency of the bank's existing fraud detection system by reducing the time it takes to identify fraudulent transactions.

      To provide the bank with actionable insights and recommendations on how to prevent future fraud.

      METHODOLOGY:¶

      Data collection: The first step will involve collecting relevant data from the bank's database, including transaction history, customer demographics, and other relevant information.

      Data pre-processing: The collected data will then undergo cleaning, normalization, and transformation to ensure its quality and suitability for analysis.

      Exploratory data analysis: This step involves examining the data to understand the relationships and patterns between the different variables. This will also help to identify any missing values, outliers, or other anomalies that may impact the model's accuracy.

      Feature selection: This step involves selecting the most important variables that will be used to build the predictive model. The aim is to identify variables that have a significant impact on the outcome of the model.

      Model selection: A range of machine learning algorithms will be considered for the task of fraud detection. The model with the highest accuracy rate will be selected and fine-tuned to improve its performance.

      Model evaluation: The selected model will be evaluated using a range of performance metrics, including accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score.

      Deployment: The final step is to deploy the model in the bank's systems to start detecting fraudulent transactions in real-time.

      def plot_confusion_matrix(y_test,prediction):
          cm_ = confusion_matrix(y_test,prediction)
          plt.figure(figsize = (6,4))
          sns.heatmap(cm_, cmap ='coolwarm', linecolor = 'white', linewidths = 1, annot = True, fmt = 'd')
          plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
          plt.ylabel('True Label')
          plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
          plt.show()

      def c_matrix_plot(prediction, y_test):
      ​
          c_matrix = confusion_matrix(prediction, y_test)
          group_names = ['True Positive', 'False Negative', 'False Positive', 'True Negative']
          group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                          c_matrix.flatten()]
          group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                               c_matrix.flatten()/np.sum(c_matrix)]
          labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}\n{v3}" for v1, v2, v3 in
                    zip(group_names,group_counts,group_percentages)]
          labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
          
          ax = sns.heatmap(c_matrix, annot=labels, fmt='', cmap='Blues')
      ​
          ax.set_title(f'Confusion Matix for {model.__class__.__name__}');
          ax.set_xlabel('\nPredicted Values')
          ax.set_ylabel('Actual Values ');
      ​
          ax.xaxis.set_ticklabels(['Non-Fraudulent', 'Fraudulent'])
          ax.yaxis.set_ticklabels(['Non-Fraudulent', 'Fraudulent'])
      ​
          plt.show()

      def trainer(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
          model.fit(X_train, y_train) #fit the model
          prediction = model.predict(X_test) # create predictions on the fitted model
          print('\nFor {}, Accuracy score is {} \n'.format(model.__class__.__name__, accuracy_score(prediction, y_test)))
          print(classification_report(prediction, y_test))
          print(confusion_matrix(prediction, y_test))
          c_matrix_plot(prediction, y_test)

      ## Model Evaluation
      ​
      The prediction of online payment fraud for Blossom Bank was performed using four different machine learning models: Logistic Regression
      K Neighbors Classifier, 
      Decision Tree Classifier, 
      and Random Forest Classifier. 
      ​
      The evaluation of these models was based on accuracy, precision, and recall, as reported in the classification report.
      ​
      Overall, all the models performed well in predicting online fraud, with a recall ranging from 84% to 99% and an accuracy of 100%. The Random Forest Classifier model stood out as the best performer, with an accuracy of 99.98% (almost 100%) and a recall of 99%. The recall indicates that 98% of true fraud cases were correctly identified by the model. The model's f1-score was 90%.
      ​
      Additionally, the confusion matrix showed the distribution of:
      ​
      True positives (non-fraudulent transactions correctly predicted as non-fraudulent), 
      False positives (fraudulent transactions incorrectly predicted as non-fraudulent), 
      False negatives (non-fraudulent transactions incorrectly predicted as fraudulent), 
      True negatives (fraudulent transactions correctly predicted as fraudulent). 
      ​
      It is crucial to minimize false positives as they would result in successful fraud without the system detecting it, whereas false negatives would simply flag a transaction but could be easily corrected by the customer.

      Model Evaluation¶

      The prediction of online payment fraud for Blossom Bank was performed using four different machine learning models: Logistic Regression K Neighbors Classifier, Decision Tree Classifier, and Random Forest Classifier.

      The evaluation of these models was based on accuracy, precision, and recall, as reported in the classification report.

      Overall, all the models performed well in predicting online fraud, with a recall ranging from 84% to 99% and an accuracy of 100%. The Random Forest Classifier model stood out as the best performer, with an accuracy of 99.98% (almost 100%) and a recall of 99%. The recall indicates that 98% of true fraud cases were correctly identified by the model. The model's f1-score was 90%.

      Additionally, the confusion matrix showed the distribution of:

      True positives (non-fraudulent transactions correctly predicted as non-fraudulent), False positives (fraudulent transactions incorrectly predicted as non-fraudulent), False negatives (non-fraudulent transactions incorrectly predicted as fraudulent), True negatives (fraudulent transactions correctly predicted as fraudulent).

      It is crucial to minimize false positives as they would result in successful fraud without the system detecting it, whereas false negatives would simply flag a transaction but could be easily corrected by the customer.
